p|In computer text processing, a b|markup_language is a system for [r:Annotation|annotating] a |document in a way that is |syntactically_distinguishable from the text.[a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markup_language#cite_note-1)|\[1\]][_]The idea and terminology evolved from the "marking up" of paper manuscripts, i.e., the revision instructions by editors, traditionally written with a[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_pencil_\(editing\))|blue pencil][_]on authors'[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manuscript)|manuscripts].\[[i|[a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)|citation needed]]\][_]In[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_media)|digital media], this "blue pencil instruction text" was replaced by[_][a url(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML_element)|tags], that is, instructions are expressed directly by tags or "instruction text encapsulated by tags." However the whole idea of a mark up language is to avoid the formatting work for the text, as the tags in the mark up language serve the purpose to format the appropriate text (like a header or beginning of a next para...etc.). Every tag used in a Markup language has a property to format the text we write.


